''Star Luster'' initially received mixed reviews and struggled to gain sales.<ref name="Myway">{{cite book |title=死ぬ前にクリアしたい200の無理ゲー ファミコン&スーファミ |trans-title=200 impossible games that you want to clear before you die — Famicom & Super Famicom |date=October 10, 2018 |publisher=My Way Publishing |isbn=9784865119855 |page=9}}</ref><ref name="Yuge"/> The game's lack of popularity has been blamed on its complex design, which relies heavily on random encounters and obtuse level objectives that, at the time, were seen as too confusing and esoteric for a console game.<ref name="Myway"/> Critics also believed producing the game for the Famicom, a game console targeted primarily towards children, was a factor in ''Star Luster''{{'}}s poor commercial reception.<ref name="Myway"/> A reviewer for ''Family Computer Magazine'' highlighted the game's usage of a radar and 3D perspective. They believed the radar was difficult to understand at first, but overtime the player would become used to it.<ref name="FCM"/>

Retrospective reviews of ''Star Luster'' have labeled it a masterpiece.<ref name="Yuge">{{cite book |last1=Endo |first1=Akihiro |title=ユーゲーが贈るファミコン名作ソフト100選 アクション部門 |trans-title=100 Selection of Famicom Masterpiece Software Presented by Yuge |date=June 1, 2003 |publisher=Yuge |pages=14–19 |edition=Number 7 |language=ja}}</ref><ref name="Ishii">{{cite book |last1=Ishii |first1=Zenji |title=20th Anniversary 僕たちの好きなファミコン100 |trans-title=20th Anniversary: Our Favorite Famicom 100 |date=December 18, 2003 |publisher=Ohta Publishing |isbn=9784872338225 |pages=9–59 |language=ja}}</ref> ''Yuge'' believed the first-person viewpoint was impressive for the time, and highlighted the game's sense of tension and ''Star Wars''-esque presentation. The magazine believes the game's first-person perspective was what led to the game's initial mixed reception, as it was considered too advanced for the time.<ref name="Yuge"/> ''Continue'' writer Zenji Ishii considers ''Star Luster'' important and influential for the space combat simulator genre, with a high level of action and strategy.<ref name="Ishii"/>

==Legacy==
In 1998, the game was included on a compilation made for the [[PlayStation]] known as ''[[Namco Anthology|Namco Anthology 1]]'' where, like all of the Famicom games presented on the disc, an enhanced arrange mode was provided alongside the unaltered original game. The Famicom version was later included in the Japanese version of Nintendo and Namco's ''[[Star Fox Assault]]'',<ref>{{cite web |author1=GameSpot Staff |title=New details, dates emerge on upcoming Nintendo titles for Japan |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/new-details-dates-emerge-on-upcoming-nintendo-titles-for-japan/1100-6116470/ |website=[[GameSpot]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |access-date=January 14, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200812121449/https://www.gamespot.com/articles/new-details-dates-emerge-on-upcoming-nintendo-titles-for-japan/1100-6116470/ |archive-date=August 12, 2020 |date=January 15, 2005}}</ref> and was released for the [[Wii Virtual Console]] in Japan on March 4, 2008.<ref name="Famitsu">{{cite magazine |title=スターラスター (FC) |url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=9043&redirect=no |magazine=[[Famitsu]] |publisher=[[Kadokawa Corporation]] |access-date=January 15, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190829012004/https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=9043&redirect=no |archive-date=August 29, 2019 |language=ja}}</ref>

A sequel, ''[[Star Ixiom]]'', was released for the PlayStation in 1999 for Japan and Europe. The game is very similar to that of its predecessor and adds seven selectable ships: the ''Gaia Σ'', Spartacus, Tycoon, Ogre-Header, Dragoon J2 (connected to Dragoon, from ''[[Galaxian 3]]''), the GeoSword from ''[[Starblade]]'', and the Galaxip from ''[[Galaxian]]''.

The game was a significant inspiration for director [[Katsuya Eguchi]] when he was working on ''[[Star Fox 2]]''.<ref>{{cite magazine |last1=Reeves |first1=Ben |title=The Inside Story On The Star Fox Sequel That Took 22 Years To Release |url=https://www.gameinformer.com/index.php/b/features/archive/2017/09/30/the-inside-story-on-the-star-fox-sequel-that-took-more-than-20-years-to-release.aspx |magazine=Game Informer |language=en}}</ref> ''[[Castlevania]]'' series producer [[Koji Igarashi]] has listed ''Star Luster'' as his second-favorite NES game.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hoffman |first1=Chris |title=Nintendo Entertainment System 20th Anniversary |url=https://archive.org/details/Play_046_Oct_2005/page/n85 |accessdate=16 January 2020 |agency=Play |issue=46 |date=October 2005 |pages=84–87}}</ref>

